                         text-align: center;        \r\n                                                  font-weight:bold;\r\n                                                  padding-top:1em;\r\n                                                }\r\n</style>\r\nHello,<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA new response was submitted for your survey \'{SURVEYNAME}\'.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nClick the following link to reload the survey:<br />\r\n{RELOADURL}<br />\r\n<br />\r\nClick the following link to see the individual response:<br />\r\n{VIEWRESPONSEURL}<br />\r\n<br />\r\nClick the following link to edit the individual response:<br />\r\n{EDITRESPONSEURL}<br />\r\n<br />\r\nView statistics by clicking here:<br />\r\n{STATISTICSURL}<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe following answers were given by the participant:<br />\r\n{ANSWERTABLE}</body>\r\n</html>\r\n',0,'a:0:{}','<p>Thank you for completing the Collaboration Success Wizard. One of the goals of the Wizard is to provide an opportunity to reflect on your collaborative practices, guided by findings from decades of research on the challenges collaborating across distance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Wizard was developed based on the Theory of Remote Scientific Collaboration (TORSC) [1]. Based on studies of over 200 collaborations, TORSC provides a set of five high-level categories that contribute to the success of collaborative projects. In this report, we outline each of the categories and provide feedback and collaborative strategies based on the answers you provided to our questions and best practices that have been successfully used in other projects.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We hope that you find this personal report a useful tool for reflection and discussion with your colleagues. However, we want to point out that as a diagnostic tool, it can only provide part of the picture. This report is generated automatically. It is based on your individual responses and does not take into account how your colleagues answered. The report uses only your numeric answers and cannot capture the richness of your text comments. As such, we can only provide general comments that may be more or less relevant to your particular situation. Also, if you did not answer all the questions, the overview feedback may be less accurate. Once the survey period is complete, we will aggregate the responses and provide customized high-level feedback to the project as a whole. In the meantime, if you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact us at <a href=\"mailto:hana-csw@uci.edu\">hana-csw@uci.edu</a>.<br />\r\n </p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Theory of Remote Scientific Collaboration</strong><br />\r\nThe Collaboration Success Wizard provides guidance about collaborative practices that tend to lead to successful outcomes. A collaboration that works well is more likely to produce good outcomes. The Theory of Remote Scientific Collaboration (TORSC) identifies five areas of collaborative practice that guide our analysis:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><em>Nature of the Work</em>: How is the work divided among sites, and how interdependent are the collaborators?</li>\r\n	<li><em>Common Ground</em>: To what extend do collaborators share mutual knowledge, beliefs, language and assumptions?</li>\r\n	<li><em>Collaboration Readiness</em>: Are participants motivated to work together? Are goals aligned? Do the participants get along?</li>\r\n	<li><em>Management, Planning, & Decision Making</em>: How is the work organized and carried out? What organizational support is available?</li>\r\n	<li><em>Technology Readiness</em>: Are appropriate collaboration technologies available to the participants, are they comfortable using them, and is support available?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Below, we first provide a summary comment for each of these five categories. Then we provide more specific comments on individual questions that suggest collaborative strengths and areas that may need improvement. </p>\r\n','<p>If you have any questions about our suggestions and feedback, or suggestions for improvement of the Wizard or this report, please address them to <a href=\"mailto:Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu\">Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[1] Olson, J. S., Hofer, E. C., Bos, N., Zimmerman, A., Olson, G. M., Cooney, D., & Faniel, I. (2008). A theory of remote scientific collaboration. In G. M. Olson, A. Zimmerman & N. Bos (Eds.), <i>Scientific Collaboration on the Internet</i> (pp. 73-97). Cambridge, MA: MIT Press.</p>\r\n'),(996989,'zh-Hans','test','','test','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','参加调查的邀请','您好， {FIRSTNAME},<br />\n<br />\n现邀请您参加一个调查。<br />\n<br />\n该调查的名字为：<br />\n\"{SURVEYNAME}\"<br />\n<br />\n\"{SURVEYDESCRIPTION}\"<br />\n<br />\n确认参加，请点击下面的连接。<br />\n<br />\n{ADMINNAME} ({ADMINEMAIL})<br />\n<br />\n----------------------------------------------<br />\n点击此处做调查：<br />\n{SURVEYURL}<br />\n<br />\n如果您不想参与本调查，并且不再希望接收邀请，请点击下面链接：<br />\n{OPTOUTURL}<br />\n<br />\n如果您被列入了黑名单并想参与本调查、希望能接收到邀请的话，请点击下面链接：<br />\n{OPTOUTURL}','提请参加调查','您好， {FIRSTNAME},<br />\n<br />\n最近我们邀请您参加一项调查。<br />\n<br />\n我们注意到您尚未完成这项调查，如果您想参与的话，该项调查还在进行中。<br />\n<br />\n调查标题：<br />\n\"{SURVEYNAME}\"<br />\n<br />\n\"{SURVEYDESCRIPTION}\"<br />\n<br />\n确认参加，请点击下面的链接。<br />\n<br />\n<br />\n{ADMINNAME} ({ADMINEMAIL})<br />\n<br />\n----------------------------------------------<br />\n点击这里做调查：<br />\n{SURVEYURL}<br />\n<br />\n如果您不想参与本调查，并且不再希望接收邀请，请点击下面链接：<br />\n{OPTOUTURL}','调查注册确认','您好 {FIRSTNAME},<br />\n<br />\n您或者其他人用您的邮件地址注册参与了名为{SURVEYNAME}的在线调查。<br />\n<br />\n要完成这个调查，请点击下面的URL:<br />\n<br />\n{SURVEYURL}<br />\n<br />\n如果您有其他问题，或者您没有注册参与并认为这封邮件有误，请通过{ADMINEMAIL}联系{ADMINNAME}。','确认参加调查','您好 {FIRSTNAME},<br />\n<br />\n这封邮件是为了确认您已经完成了名为{SURVEYNAME}的调查，您的反馈已经被保存。感谢参与。<br />\n<br />\n如果您对这封邮件有任何问题，请 通过{ADMINEMAIL}联系 {ADMINNAME}.<br />\n<br />\n<br />\n{ADMINNAME}',1,NULL,'调查反馈提交{SURVEYNAME}','Hello,<br />\n<br />\nA new response was submitted for your survey \'{SURVEYNAME}\'.<br />\n<br />\nClick the following link to see the individual response:<br />\n{VIEWRESPONSEURL}<br />\n<br />\nClick the following link to edit the individual response:<br />\n{EDITRESPONSEURL}<br />\n<br />\nView statistics by clicking here:<br />\n{STATISTICSURL}','带结果的调查反馈提交{SURVEYNAME}','Hello,<br />\n<br />\nA new response was submitted for your survey \'{SURVEYNAME}\'.<br />\n<br />\nClick the following link to see the individual response:<br />\n{VIEWRESPONSEURL}<br />\n<br />\nClick the following link to edit the individual response:<br />\n{EDITRESPONSEURL}<br />\n<br />\nView statistics by clicking here:<br />\n{STATISTICSURL}<br />\n<br />\n<br />\nThe following answers were given by the participant:<br />\n{ANSWERTABLE}',0,NULL,'test header','test footer'),(25987,'en','Collaboration Success Wizard - Past Tense Template',NULL,'<strong>Thank you</strong> for your interest in taking our online survey. This survey usually takes approximately 20-30 minutes. You are free to answer the questions in several sittings; you can stop at any time knowing that your answers up to that time are saved and you can return at a later time to pick up where you left off. You can go back to previous questions, to review and revise your responses, via the navigation tree on the right side of the screen.<br />\n<br />\nPlease answer the survey questions with regard to the XXXX Project. Each question has a free-text box in which you can communicate with us about the question. You can explain your answer, provide examples illustrating your answer, comment on the question itself (i.e. did you understand what it was asking?), provide general feedback about the survey itself, or even to provide information about your project that we didnʻt think to ask but that you consider important.<br />\n<br />\n<strong>What you get out of this: </strong>At the end of the questions, you can generate a report that gives an overall assessment, based on your responses, of your project’s strengths and points of potential weakness. For each potential weakness, we try to suggest an action you can take to remedy the situation, based on what has worked for others.<br />\n<br />\n<strong>What we get out of this:</strong> We have been studying long‐distance work for nearly twenty years. We have developed a theory about what makes these projects successful and what presents barriers to success. In order to test the theory, we need a lot of data both from different individuals within a project and across a lot of projects.<br />\n<br />\n<strong>Concerns about privacy?</strong> Your data will be aggregated in any reports, either oral or written, so that your individual identity will not be revealed. We will ask for your permission if we can identify your role and project in publications after you have answered all the questions, so you have a sense of the sensitivity your answers may invoke.<br />\n<br />\n<strong>Ethics:</strong> The University of California at Irvine’s Institutional Review Board has approved this research, under protocol HS#2013-9917. This approval certifies that you are answering these questions of your own free will, knowing what they will be used for, and that your privacy will be respected. You are free to stop answering these questions altogether, although we, of course, would like to see you finish so our data are balanced and complete. If you have any questions or qualms, please contact us by email at <a href=\"mailto:Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu\">Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu</a> or UCI’s Office of Research Administration by phone, (949) 824‐6662, by e‐mail at <a href=\"mailto:irb@rgs.uci.edu\">irb@rgs.uci.edu</a>, or at 5171 California Ave., Suite 150, Irvine, CA 92697‐7600.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,'Invitation to participate in Collaboration Success Wizard','<html><head><title></title></head><body>\n<p>Dear {ATTRIBUTE_1}&nbsp;{LASTNAME},\n</p>\n<p>As one of the participants in the&nbsp;SCALE project, you are invited to explore issues about your collaboration and distributed work through our online survey entitled the &quot;Collaboration Success Wizard.&quot;&nbsp;&nbsp;Your answers will help us provide specific feedback to the SCALE project about the strengths and challenges in your collaboration, as well as advancing research about collaborative scientific practices generally.\n</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">You can access the Wizard at: {SURVEYURL}\n</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">The Wizard generally takes 20-30 minutes to complete. You need not answer all the questions in a single sitting; your answers will be saved and you can return at a later time to complete the survey.\n</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">After completing the Wizard, you will be provided with a link to automatically generate a report for you, tailored to your responses, that identifies collaborative strengths and potential vulnerabilities, as well as interventions that have been successful with other organizations in the past. &nbsp;At the end of the study period, our research group will provide a summary report detailing our findings to the SCALE PIs. &nbsp;We respect your privacy and any individual responses cited in this report, or subsequent publications, will be completely anonymized.\n</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">To enable us to provide our analysis in a timely manner, we ask that you complete the Wizard by&nbsp;<strong>August 15, 2012</strong>.&nbsp;If you have any questions or experience any difficulties using the Wizard, please contact us at <a href=\"mailto:Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu\"><span class=\"s1\">Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu</span></a>.\n</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Thank you!\n</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Gary Olson<br />\nDonald Bren Professor of Information and Computer Sciences<br />\nDepartment of Informatics<br />\nBren School of Information and Computer Sciences<br />\nUniversity of California, Irvine<br />\nIrvine, CA&nbsp; 92697-3440\n</p>\n</body></html>','Reminder to participate in Collaboration Success Wizard','<html><head><title></title></head><body>\n<p>Dear {ATTRIBUTE_1} {LASTNAME},<br />\n<br />\nRecently we invited you to participate in a survey about the SCALE project.<br />\n<br />\nWe note that you have not yet completed the survey, and wish to remind you that the survey is still available until August 15, 2012, should you wish to take part.<br />\n<br />\nTo participate, please click on this link:\n</p>\n<p>{SURVEYURL}<br />\n&nbsp;\n</p>\n<p>Sincerely,<br />\n<br />\nGary Olson<br />\nDonald Bren Professor of Information and Computer Sciences<br />\nDepartment of Informatics<br />\nBren School of Information and Computer Sciences<br />\nUniversity of California, Irvine<br />\nIrvine, CA 92697-3440\n</p>\n</body></html>','Survey registration confirmation','<html><head><title></title></head><body>Dear {FIRSTNAME},<br />\n<br />\nYou, or someone using your email address, have registered to participate in an online survey titled {SURVEYNAME}.<br />\n<br />\nTo complete this survey, click on the following URL:<br />\n<br />\n{SURVEYURL}<br />\n<br />\nIf you have any questions about this survey, or if you did not register to participate and believe this email is in error, please contact {ADMINNAME} at {ADMINEMAIL}.</body></html>','Confirmation of your participation in our survey','<html><head><title></title></head><body>\n<p>Dear {ATTRIBUTE_1} {LASTNAME},<br />\n<br />\nThis email is to confirm that you have completed the&nbsp;Collaboration Success Wizard for the SCALE project&nbsp;and your response has been saved. The report for your survey result is attached in the email. Thank you for participating.<br />\n<br />\nSincerely,\n</p>\n<p>Gary Olson<br />\nDonald Bren Professor of Information and Computer Sciences<br />\nDepartment of Informatics<br />\nBren School of Information and Computer Sciences<br />\nUniversity of California, Irvine<br />\nIrvine, CA 92697-3440\n</p>\n</body></html>',3,NULL,'Response submission for survey {SURVEYNAME}','<html><head><title></title></head><body>\n<p>Hello,<br />\n<br />\nA new response was submitted for your survey &#39;{SURVEYNAME}&#39;.<br />\n<br />\nClick the following link to reload the survey:<br />\n{RELOADURL}<br />\n<br />\nClick the following link to see the individual response:<br />\n{VIEWRESPONSEURL}<br />\n<br />\nClick the following link to edit the individual response:<br />\n{EDITRESPONSEURL}<br />\n<br />\nView statistics by clicking here:<br />\n{STATISTICSURL}\n</p>\n<p>The report for this survey result is attached in the email.\n</p>\n<p>&nbsp;\n</p>\n</body></html>','Response submission for survey {SURVEYNAME} with results','<html><head><title></title></head><body><style type=\"text/css\">.printouttable {\n                                                  margin:1em auto;\n                                                }\n                                                .printouttable th {\n                                                  text-align: center;\n                                                }\n                                                .printouttable td {\n                                                  border-color: #ddf #ddf #ddf #ddf;\n                                                  border-style: solid;\n                                                  border-width: 1px;\n                                                  padding:0.1em 1em 0.1em 0.5em;\n                                                }\n\n                                                .printouttable td:first-child {\n                                                  font-weight: 700;\n                                                  text-align: right;\n                                                  padding-right: 5px;\n                                                  padding-left: 5px;\n\n                                                }\n                                                .printouttable .printanswersquestion td{\n                                                  background-color:#F7F8FF;\n                                                }\n\n                                                .printouttable .printanswersquestionhead td{\n                                                  text-align: left;\n                                                  background-color:#ddf;\n                                                }\n\n                                                .printouttable .printanswersgroup td{\n                                                  text-align: center;        \n                                                  font-weight:bold;\n                                                  padding-top:1em;\n                                                }</style>Hello,<br />\n<br />\nA new response was submitted for your survey &#39;{SURVEYNAME}&#39;.<br />\n<br />\nClick the following link to reload the survey:<br />\n{RELOADURL}<br />\n<br />\nClick the following link to see the individual response:<br />\n{VIEWRESPONSEURL}<br />\n<br />\nClick the following link to edit the individual response:<br />\n{EDITRESPONSEURL}<br />\n<br />\nView statistics by clicking here:<br />\n{STATISTICSURL}<br />\n<br />\n<br />\nThe following answers were given by the participant:<br />\n{ANSWERTABLE}</body></html>',0,NULL,'<p>\n	Thank you for completing the Collaboration Success Wizard. One of the goals of the Wizard is to provide an opportunity to reflect on your collaborative practices, guided by findings from decades of research on the challenges collaborating across distance.</p>\n<p>\n	The Wizard was developed based on the Theory of Remote Scientific Collaboration (TORSC) [1]. Based on studies of over 200 collaborations, TORSC provides a set of five high-level categories that contribute to the success of collaborative projects. In this report, we outline each of the categories and provide feedback and collaborative strategies based on the answers you provided to our questions and best practices that have been successfully used&nbsp;in other projects.</p>\n<p>\n	We hope that you find this personal report a useful tool for reflection and discussion with your colleagues. However, we want to point out that as a diagnostic tool, it can only provide part of the picture. This report is generated automatically. It is based on your individual responses and does not take into account how your colleagues answered. The report uses only your numeric answers and cannot capture the richness of your text comments. As such, we can only provide general comments that may be more or less relevant to your particular situation. Also, if you did not answer all the questions, the overview feedback may be less accurate. Once the survey period is complete, we will aggregate the responses and provide customized high-level feedback to the project as a whole. In the meantime, if you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact us at <a href=\"mailto:hana-csw@uci.edu\">hana-csw@uci.edu</a>.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Theory of Remote Scientific Collaboration</strong><br />\n	The Collaboration Success Wizard provides guidance about collaborative practices that tend to lead to successful outcomes. A collaboration that works well is more likely to produce good outcomes. The Theory of Remote Scientific Collaboration (TORSC) identifies five areas of collaborative practice that guide our analysis:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		<em>Nature of the Work</em>: How is the work divided among sites, and how interdependent are the collaborators?</li>\n	<li>\n		<em>Common Ground</em>: To what extend do collaborators share mutual knowledge, beliefs, language and assumptions?</li>\n	<li>\n		<em>Collaboration Readiness</em>: Are participants motivated to work together? Are goals aligned? Do the participants get along?</li>\n	<li>\n		<em>Management, Planning, &amp; Decision Making</em>: How is the work organized and carried out? What organizational support is available?</li>\n	<li>\n		<em>Technology Readiness</em>: Are appropriate collaboration technologies available to the participants, are they comfortable using them, and is support available?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	Below, we first provide a summary comment for each of these five categories. Then we provide more specific comments on individual questions that suggest collaborative strengths and areas that may need improvement.&nbsp;</p>\n','<p>\n	If you have any questions about our suggestions and feedback, or suggestions for improvement of the Wizard or this report, please address them to <a href=\"mailto:Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu\">Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu</a>.</p>\n<p>\n	[1] Olson, J. S., Hofer, E. C., Bos, N., Zimmerman, A., Olson, G. M., Cooney, D., & Faniel, I. (2008). A theory of remote scientific collaboration. In G. M. Olson, A. Zimmerman & N. Bos (Eds.), <i>Scientific Collaboration on the Internet</i> (pp. 73-97). Cambridge, MA: MIT Press.</p>\n'),(53623,'en','Collaboration Success Wizard - Present Tense Template',NULL,'<strong>Thank you</strong> for your interest in taking our online survey. This survey usually takes approximately 20-30 minutes. You are free to answer the questions in several sittings; you can stop at any time knowing that your answers up to that time are saved and you can return at a later time to pick up where you left off. You can go back to previous questions, to review and revise your responses, via the navigation tree on the right side of the screen.<br />\n<br />\nPlease answer the survey questions with regard to the XXXX Project. Each question has a free-text box in which you can communicate with us about the question. You can explain your answer, provide examples illustrating your answer, comment on the question itself (i.e. did you understand what it was asking?), provide general feedback about the survey itself, or even to provide information about your project that we didnʻt think to ask but that you consider important.<br />\n<br />\n<strong>What you get out of this: </strong>At the end of the questions, you can generate a report that gives an overall assessment, based on your responses, of your project’s strengths and points of potential weakness. For each potential weakness, we try to suggest an action you can take to remedy the situation, based on what has worked for others.<br />\n<br />\n<strong>What we get out of this:</strong> We have been studying long‐distance work for nearly twenty years. We have developed a theory about what makes these projects successful and what presents barriers to success. In order to test the theory, we need a lot of data both from different individuals within a project and across a lot of projects.<br />\n<br />\n<strong>Concerns about privacy?</strong> Your data will be aggregated in any reports, either oral or written, so that your individual identity will not be revealed. We will ask for your permission if we can identify your role and project in publications after you have answered all the questions, so you have a sense of the sensitivity your answers may invoke.<br />\n<br />\n<strong>Ethics:</strong> The University of California at Irvine’s Institutional Review Board has approved this research, under protocol HS#2013-9917. This approval certifies that you are answering these questions of your own free will, knowing what they will be used for, and that your privacy will be respected. You are free to stop answering these questions altogether, although we, of course, would like to see you finish so our data are balanced and complete. If you have any questions or qualms, please contact us by email at <a href=\"mailto:Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu\">Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu</a> or UCI’s Office of Research Administration by phone, (949) 824‐6662, by e‐mail at <a href=\"mailto:irb@rgs.uci.edu\">irb@rgs.uci.edu</a>, or at 5171 California Ave., Suite 150, Irvine, CA 92697‐7600.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,'Invitation to participate in Collaboration Success Wizard','<html>\r\n<head>\r\n	<title></title>\r\n</head>\r\n<body>Dear {FIRSTNAME},<br />\r\n<br />\r\nyou have been invited to participate in a survey.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe survey is titled:<br />\r\n\"{SURVEYNAME}\"<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\"{SURVEYDESCRIPTION}\"<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo participate, please click on the link below.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSincerely,<br />\r\n<br />\r\n{ADMINNAME} ({ADMINEMAIL})<br />\r\n<br />\r\n----------------------------------------------<br />\r\nClick here to do the survey:<br />\r\n{SURVEYURL}<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf you do not want to participate in this survey and don\'t want to receive any more invitations please click the following link:<br />\r\n{OPTOUTURL}<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf you are blacklisted but want to participate in this survey and want to receive invitations please click the following link:<br />\r\n{OPTINURL}</body>\r\n</html>\r\n','Reminder to participate in a survey','<html>\r\n<head>\r\n	<title></title>\r\n</head>\r\n<body>\r\n<p>Dear {ATTRIBUTE_1} {LASTNAME},<br />\r\n<br />\r\nRecently we invited you to participate in a survey about the SCALE project.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWe note that you have not yet completed the survey, and wish to remind you that the survey is still available until Sep 15, 2015, should you wish to take part.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo participate, please click on this link:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>{SURVEYURL}<br />\r\n </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sincerely,<br />\r\n<br />\r\nGary Olson<br />\r\nDonald Bren Professor of Information and Computer Sciences<br />\r\nDepartment of Informatics<br />\r\nBren School of Information and Computer Sciences<br />\r\nUniversity of California, Irvine<br />\r\nIrvine, CA 92697-3440</p>\r\n</body>\r\n</html>\r\n','Survey registration confirmation','<html>\r\n<head>\r\n	<title></title>\r\n</head>\r\n<body>Dear {FIRSTNAME},<br />\r\n<br />\r\nYou, or someone using your email address, have registered to participate in an online survey titled {SURVEYNAME}.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo complete this survey, click on the following URL:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n{SURVEYURL}<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf you have any questions about this survey, or if you did not register to participate and believe this email is in error, please contact {ADMINNAME} at {ADMINEMAIL}.</body>\r\n</html>\r\n','Confirmation of your participation in our survey','<html>\r\n<head>\r\n	<title></title>\r\n</head>\r\n<body>\r\n<p>Dear {ATTRIBUTE_1} {LASTNAME},<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis email is to confirm that you have completed the Collaboration Success Wizard for the SCALE project and your response has been saved. The report for your survey result is attached in the email. Thank you for participating.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSincerely,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Gary Olson<br />\r\nDonald Bren Professor of Information and Computer Sciences<br />\r\nDepartment of Informatics<br />\r\nBren School of Information and Computer Sciences<br />\r\nUniversity of California, Irvine<br />\r\nIrvine, CA 92697-3440</p>\r\n</body>\r\n</html>\r\n',3,NULL,'Response submission for survey {SURVEYNAME}','<html>\r\n<head>\r\n	<title></title>\r\n</head>\r\n<body>\r\n<p>Hello,<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA new response was submitted for your survey \'{SURVEYNAME}\'.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nClick the following link to reload the survey:<br />\r\n{RELOADURL}<br />\r\n<br />\r\nClick the following link to see the individual response:<br />\r\n{VIEWRESPONSEURL}<br />\r\n<br />\r\nClick the following link to edit the individual response:<br />\r\n{EDITRESPONSEURL}<br />\r\n<br />\r\nView statistics by clicking here:<br />\r\n{STATISTICSURL}</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The report for this survey result is attached in the email.</p>\r\n\r\n<p> </p>\r\n</body>\r\n</html>\r\n','Response submission for survey {SURVEYNAME} with results','<html>\r\n<head>\r\n	<title></title>\r\n</head>\r\n<body>\r\n<style type=\"text/css\">.printouttable {\r\n                                                  margin:1em auto;\r\n                                                }\r\n                                                .printouttable th {\r\n                                                  text-align: center;\r\n                                                }\r\n                                                .printouttable td {\r\n                                                  border-color: #ddf #ddf #ddf #ddf;\r\n                                                  border-style: solid;\r\n                                                  border-width: 1px;\r\n                                                  padding:0.1em 1em 0.1em 0.5em;\r\n                                                }\r\n\r\n                                                .printouttable td:first-child {\r\n                                                  font-weight: 700;\r\n                                                  text-align: right;\r\n                                                  padding-right: 5px;\r\n                                                  padding-left: 5px;\r\n\r\n                                                }\r\n                                                .printouttable .printanswersquestion td{\r\n                                                  background-color:#F7F8FF;\r\n                                                }\r\n\r\n                                                .printouttable .printanswersquestionhead td{\r\n                                                  text-align: left;\r\n                                                  background-color:#ddf;\r\n                                                }\r\n\r\n                                                .printouttable .printanswersgroup td{\r\n                                                  text-align: center;        \r\n                                                  font-weight:bold;\r\n                                                  padding-top:1em;\r\n                                                }\r\n</style>\r\nHello,<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA new response was submitted for your survey \'{SURVEYNAME}\'.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nClick the following link to reload the survey:<br />\r\n{RELOADURL}<br />\r\n<br />\r\nClick the following link to see the individual response:<br />\r\n{VIEWRESPONSEURL}<br />\r\n<br />\r\nClick the following link to edit the individual response:<br />\r\n{EDITRESPONSEURL}<br />\r\n<br />\r\nView statistics by clicking here:<br />\r\n{STATISTICSURL}<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe following answers were given by the participant:<br />\r\n{ANSWERTABLE}</body>\r\n</html>\r\n',0,'a:0:{}','<p>\n	Thank you for completing the Collaboration Success Wizard. One of the goals of the Wizard is to provide an opportunity to reflect on your collaborative practices, guided by findings from decades of research on the challenges collaborating across distance.</p>\n<p>\n	The Wizard was developed based on the Theory of Remote Scientific Collaboration (TORSC) [1]. Based on studies of over 200 collaborations, TORSC provides a set of five high-level categories that contribute to the success of collaborative projects. In this report, we outline each of the categories and provide feedback and collaborative strategies based on the answers you provided to our questions and best practices that have been successfully used&nbsp;in other projects.</p>\n<p>\n	We hope that you find this personal report a useful tool for reflection and discussion with your colleagues. However, we want to point out that as a diagnostic tool, it can only provide part of the picture. This report is generated automatically. It is based on your individual responses and does not take into account how your colleagues answered. The report uses only your numeric answers and cannot capture the richness of your text comments. As such, we can only provide general comments that may be more or less relevant to your particular situation. Also, if you did not answer all the questions, the overview feedback may be less accurate. Once the survey period is complete, we will aggregate the responses and provide customized high-level feedback to the project as a whole. In the meantime, if you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact us at <a href=\"mailto:hana-csw@uci.edu\">hana-csw@uci.edu</a>.<br />\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Theory of Remote Scientific Collaboration</strong><br />\n	The Collaboration Success Wizard provides guidance about collaborative practices that tend to lead to successful outcomes. A collaboration that works well is more likely to produce good outcomes. The Theory of Remote Scientific Collaboration (TORSC) identifies five areas of collaborative practice that guide our analysis:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		<em>Nature of the Work</em>: How is the work divided among sites, and how interdependent are the collaborators?</li>\n	<li>\n		<em>Common Ground</em>: To what extend do collaborators share mutual knowledge, beliefs, language and assumptions?</li>\n	<li>\n		<em>Collaboration Readiness</em>: Are participants motivated to work together? Are goals aligned? Do the participants get along?</li>\n	<li>\n		<em>Management, Planning, &amp; Decision Making</em>: How is the work organized and carried out? What organizational support is available?</li>\n	<li>\n		<em>Technology Readiness</em>: Are appropriate collaboration technologies available to the participants, are they comfortable using them, and is support available?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	Below, we first provide a summary comment for each of these five categories. Then we provide more specific comments on individual questions that suggest collaborative strengths and areas that may need improvement.&nbsp;</p>\n','<p>\n	If you have any questions about our suggestions and feedback, or suggestions for improvement of the Wizard or this report, please address them to <a href=\"mailto:Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu\">Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu</a>.</p>\n<p>\n	[1] Olson, J. S., Hofer, E. C., Bos, N., Zimmerman, A., Olson, G. M., Cooney, D., & Faniel, I. (2008). A theory of remote scientific collaboration. In G. M. Olson, A. Zimmerman & N. Bos (Eds.), <i>Scientific Collaboration on the Internet</i> (pp. 73-97). Cambridge, MA: MIT Press.</p>\n'),(59461,'en','Collaboration Success Wizard - Future Tense Template',NULL,'<strong>Thank you</strong> for your interest in taking our online survey. This survey usually takes approximately 20-30 minutes. You are free to answer the questions in several sittings; you can stop at any time knowing that your submitted answers are saved and you can return, at a later time, to pick up where you left off. You can go back to previous questions, to review and revise your responses, via the navigation tree on the right side of the screen.<br />\n<br />\nPlease answer the survey questions with regard to the XXXX Supports project. Each question has a free-text box in which you can communicate with us about the question. You can explain your answer, provide examples illustrating your answer, comment on the question itself (i.e. did you understand what it was asking?), provide general feedback about the survey itself, or even to provide information about your project that we didnʻt think to ask but that you consider important.<br />\n<br />\n<strong>What you get out of this: </strong>At the end of the questions, you can generate a report that gives an overall assessment, based on your responses, of your project\'s strengths and points of potential weakness. For each potential weakness, we try to suggest an action you can take to remedy the situation, based on what has worked for others.<br />\n<br />\n<strong>What we get out of this:</strong> We have been studying long‐distance work for nearly twenty years. We have developed a theory about what makes these projects successful and what presents barriers to success. In order to test the theory, we need a lot of data both from different individuals within a project and across a lot of projects.<br />\n<br />\n<strong>Concerns about privacy?</strong> Your data will be aggregated in any reports, either oral or written, so that your individual identity will not be revealed. We will ask for your permission if we can identify your role and project in publications after you have answered all the questions, so you have a sense of the sensitivity your answers may invoke.<br />\n<br />\n<strong>Ethics:</strong> The University of California at Irvine’s Institutional Review Board has approved this research, under protocol HS#2013-9917. This approval certifies that you are answering these questions of your own free will, knowing what they will be used for, and that your privacy will be respected. You are free to stop answering these questions altogether, although we, of course, would like to see you finish so our data are balanced and complete. If you have any questions or qualms, please contact us by email at <a href=\"mailto:Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu\">Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu</a> or UCI’s Office of Research Administration by phone, (949) 824‐6662, by e‐mail at <a href=\"mailto:irb@rgs.uci.edu\">irb@rgs.uci.edu</a>, or at 5171 California Avenue, Suite 150, Irvine, CA 92697-7600.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,'Invitation to participate in Collaboration Success Wizard','<html><head><title></title></head><body>\n<p>Dear {FIRSTNAME}\n</p>\n<p>As one of the contributors to the PICU Supports&nbsp;project, you are invited to explore issues about your collaboration and distributed work through our online survey entitled the &quot;Collaboration Success Wizard.&quot;&nbsp;&nbsp;Your answers will help us provide specific feedback to the PICU Supports project about the strengths and challenges in your collaboration, as well as advancing research about collaborative scientific practices generally.\n</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">You can access the Wizard at&nbsp;:{SURVEYURL}\n</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">The Wizard generally takes 20-25 minutes to complete. You need not answer all the questions in a single sitting; your answers will be saved and you can return at a later time to complete the survey.\n</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">After completing the Wizard, you will be provided with a link to automatically generate a report for you, tailored to your responses, that identifies collaborative strengths and potential vulnerabilities, as well as interventions that have been successful with other organizations in the past. At the end of the study period, our research group will provide a summary report detailing our findings to the PICU PIs, and any respondents requesting it. &nbsp;\n</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">We respect your privacy and any individual responses cited in this report, or subsequent publications, will be completely anonymized.\n</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">To enable us to provide our analysis in a timely manner, we ask that you complete the Wizard by <strong>November 1st</strong>,&nbsp;<strong>2013</strong>. If you have any questions or experience any difficulties using the Wizard, please contact us at <a href=\"mailto:Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu\"><span class=\"s1\">Hana-CSW-Admins@ics.uci.edu</span></a>.\n</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Thank you!\n</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Gary Olson<br />\nDonald Bren Professor of Information and Computer Sciences<br />\nDepartment of Informatics<br />\nBren School of Information and Computer Sciences<br />\nUniversity of California, Irvine<br />\nIrvine, CA&nbsp; 92697-3440\n</p>\n</body></html>','Reminder to participate in Collaboration Success Wizard','<html><head><title></title></head><body>\n<p>Dear&nbsp;{FIRSTNAME},<br />\n<br />\nRecently we invited you to participate in a survey about the SCALE project.<br />\n<br />\nWe note that you have not yet completed the survey, and wish to remind you that the survey is still available until August 15, 2012, should you wish to take part.<br />\n<br />\nTo participate, please click on this link:\n</p>\n<p>{SURVEYURL}<br />\n&nbsp;\n</p>\n<p>Sincerely,<br />\n<br />\nGary Olson<br />\nDonald Bren Professor of Information and Computer Sciences<br />\nDepartment of Informatics<br />\nBren School of Information and Computer Sciences<br />\nUniversity of California, Irvine<br />\nIrvine, CA 92697-3440\n</p>\n</body></html>','Survey registration confirmation','<html><head><title></title></head><body>Dear {FIRSTNAME},<br />\n<br />\nYou, or someone using your email address, have registered to participate in an online survey titled {SURVEYNAME}.<br />\n<br />\nTo complete this survey, click on the following URL:<br />\n<br />\n{SURVEYURL}<br />\n<br />\nIf you have any questions about this survey, or if you did not register to participate and believe this email is in error, please contact {ADMINNAME} at {ADMINEMAIL}.</body></html>','Confirmation of your participation in our survey','<html><head><title></title></head><body>\n<p>Dear {LASTNAME},<br />\n<br />\nThis email is to confirm that you have completed the&nbsp;Collaboration Success Wizard for the PICU Supports project&nbsp;and your response has been saved. The report for your survey result is attached in the email. Thank you for participating.<br />\n<br />\nSincerely,\n</p>\n<p>Gary Olson<br />\nDonald Bren Professor of Information and Computer Sciences<br />\nDepartment of Informatics<br />\nBren School of Information and Computer Sciences<br />\nUniversity of California, Irvine<br />\nIrvine, CA 92697-3440\n</p>\n</body></html>',3,NULL,'Response submission for survey {SURVEYNAME}','<html><head><title></title></head><body>\n<p>Hello,<br />\n<br />\nA new response was submitted for your survey &#39;{SURVEYNAME}&#39;.<br />\n<br />\nClick the following link to reload the survey:<br />\n{RELOADURL}<br />\n<br />\nClick the following link to see the individual response:<br />\n{VIEWRESPONSEURL}<br />\n<br />\nClick the following link to edit the individual response:<br />\n{EDITRESPONSEURL}<br />\n<br />\nView statistics by clicking here:<br />\n{STATISTICSURL}\n</p>\n<p>The report for this survey result is attached in the email.\n</p>\n<p>&nbsp;\n</p>\n</body></html>','Response submission for survey {SURVEYNAME} with results','<html><head><title></title></head><body><style type=\"text/css\">.printouttable {\n                                                  margin:1em auto;\n                                                }\n                                                .printouttable th {\n                                                  text-align: center;\n                                                }\n                                                .printouttable td {\n                                                  border-color: #ddf #ddf #ddf #ddf;\n                                                  border-style: solid;\n                                                  border-width: 1px;\n                                                  padding:0.1em 1em 0.1em 0.5em;\n                                                }\n\n                                                .printouttable td:first-child {\n                                                  font-weight: 700;\n                                                  text-align: right;\n                                                  padding-right: 5px;\n                                                  padding-left: 5px;\n\n                                                }\n                                                .printouttable .printanswersquestion td{\n                                                  background-color:#F7F8FF;\n                                                }\n\n                                                .printouttable .printanswersquestionhead td{\n                                                  text-align: left;\n                                                  background-color:#ddf;\n                                                }\n\n                                                .printouttable .printanswersgroup td{\n                                                  text-align: center;        \n                                                  font-weight:bold;\n                                                  padding-top:1em;\n                                                }</style>Hello,<br />\n<br />\nA new response was submitted for your survey &#39;{SURVEYNAME}&#39;.<br />\n<br />\nClick the following link to reload the survey:<br />\n{RELOADURL}<br />\n<br />\nClick the following link to see the individual response:<br />\n{VIEWRESPONSEURL}<br />\n<br />\nClick the following link to edit the individual response:<br />\n{EDITRESPONSEURL}<br />\n<br />\nView statistics by clicking here:<br />\n{STATISTICSURL}<br />\n<br />\n<br />\nThe following answers were given by the participant:<br />\n{ANSWERTABLE}</body></html>',0,NULL,'<p>\n	Thank you for completing the Collaboration Success Wizard. One of the goals of the Wizard is to provide an opportunity to reflect on your collaborative practices, guided by findings from decades of research on the challenges collaborating across distance.</p>\n<div>\n	The Wizard was developed from the Theory of Remote Scientific Collaboration (TORSC) [1]. Based on studies of over 200 collaborations, TORSC provides a set of five high-level categories that contribute to the success of collaborative projects. In this report, we outline each of the categories and provide feedback and collaborative strategies based on the answers you provided to our questions and best practices that have been successfully used in other projects.</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	We hope that you find this personal report a useful tool for reflection and discussion with your colleagues. However, we want to point out that as a diagnostic tool, it can only provide part of the picture. This report is generated automatically. It is based on your individual responses and does not take into account how your colleagues answered. The report uses only your numeric answers and cannot capture the richness of your text comments. As such, we can only provide general comments here that may be more or less relevant to your particular situation. Also, if you did not answer all the questions, the overview summaries may not be quite accurate. Once the survey period is complete, we will aggregate the responses and provide customized high-level feedback to the project as a whole. In the meantime, if you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact us at &lt;a href=&quot;mailto:Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu&quot;&gt;Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu&lt;/a&gt;.</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	<strong>Theory of Remote Scientific Collaboration</strong></div>\n<div>\n	The Collaboration Success Wizard provides guidance about collaborative practices that tend to lead to successful outcomes. A collaboration that works well is more likely to produce good outcomes. The Theory of Remote Scientific Collaboration (TORSC) identifies five areas of collaborative practice that guide our analysis:</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	<strong>Nature of the Work:</strong> How is the work divided among sites, and how interdependent are the collaborators?</div>\n<div>\n	<strong>Common Ground:</strong> To what extend do collaborators share mutual knowledge, beliefs, language and assumptions?</div>\n<div>\n	<strong>Collaboration Readiness:</strong> Are participants motivated to work together? Are goals aligned? Do the participants get along?</div>\n<div>\n	<strong>Management, Planning, &amp; Decision Making:</strong> How is the work organized and carried out? What organizational support is available?</div>\n<div>\n	<strong>Technology Readiness:</strong> Are appropriate collaboration technologies available to the participants, are they comfortable using them, and is support available?</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	Below, we provide a summary comment for each of these five categories. Then we provide more specific comments on individual questions that suggest collaborative strengths and identify areas that may need attention.&nbsp;</div>\n','<p>\n	 </p>\n<div>\n	If you have any questions about our suggestions and feedback, or suggestions for improvement of the Wizard or this report, please address them to <a href=\"mailto:Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edi\">Hana-CSW@ics.uci.edu</a>.</div>\n<div>\n	 </div>\n<div>\n	[1] Olson, J. S., Hofer, E. C., Bos, N., Zimmerman, A., Olson, G. M., Cooney, D., & Faniel, I. (2008). A theory of remote scientific collaboration. In G. M. Olson, A. Zimmerman & N. Bos (Eds.), Scientific Collaboration on the Internet (pp. 73-97). Cambridge, MA: MIT Press.</div>\n');
